  "category_title": "Counting Things (つ / 個)",
  "category_subtitle": "Learn how to count general things in Japanese",
  "category_detail": "<b>Counting Things in Japanese</b><br><br>Japanese has many counters depending on the type of object. When counting general items or when the correct counter is unknown, learners often start with the traditional <b>「つ」</b> counter.<br><br>The 「つ」 counter is commonly used from <b>1 to 10</b> and has special readings that must be memorized.<br><br>After 10, Japanese usually switches to the more general counter <b>個 (こ)</b>, which follows the regular number pattern.<br><br><span class=\"example\">1つ</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(ひとつ / hitotsu)</span><br><span class=\"example\">2つ</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(ふたつ / futatsu)</span><br><span class=\"example\">3つ</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(みっつ / mittsu)</span><br><br>After ten:<br><span class=\"example\">11個</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(じゅういっこ / juuikko)</span><br><span class=\"example\">12個</span> <span class=\"romaji\">(じゅうにこ / juuniko)</span>",
